<doc id="1166579" wikidata="Q5421523" url="?curid=1166579" title="Exponential formula">
<text>In combinatorial mathematics, the exponential formula (called the polymer expansion in physics) states that the exponential generating function for structures on finite sets is the exponential of the exponential generating function for connected structures.
The exponential formula is a power series version of a special case of Faà di Bruno&#x27;s formula.

==Algebraic statement==
Here is a purely algebraic statement, as a first introduction to the combinatorial use of the formula.

For any formal power series of the form
formula_1
we have
formula_2
where
formula_3
and the index formula_4 runs through all partitions formula_5 of the set
formula_6. (When formula_7 the product is empty and by definition equals formula_8.)

===Formula in other expressions===
One can write the formula in the following form:
formula_9
and thus
formula_10
where formula_11 is the formula_12th complete Bell polynomial.

Alternatively, the exponential formula can also be written using the cycle index of the symmetric group, as follows:formula_13where formula_14 stands for the cycle index polynomial for the symmetric group formula_15, defined as:formula_16and formula_17 denotes the number of cycles of formula_18 of size formula_19. This is a consequence of the general relation between formula_14 and Bell polynomials:formula_21

==Combinatorial interpretation==

In combinatorial applications, the numbers formula_22 count the number of some sort of &quot;connected&quot; structure on an formula_12-point set, and the numbers formula_24 count the number of (possibly disconnected) structures. The numbers formula_25 count the number of isomorphism classes of structures on formula_12 points, with each structure being weighted by the reciprocal of its automorphism group, and the numbers formula_27 count isomorphism classes of connected structures in the same way.

==Examples==
* formula_28 because there is one partition of the set formula_29 that has a single block of size formula_30, there are three partitions of formula_29 that split it into a block of size formula_32 and a block of size formula_8, and there is one partition of formula_29 that splits it into three blocks of size formula_8. This also follows from formula_36, since one can write the group formula_37 as formula_38, using cyclic notation for permutations.
* If formula_39 is the number of graphs whose vertices are a given formula_12-point set, then formula_22 is the number of connected graphs whose vertices are a given formula_12-point set.
* There are numerous variations of the previous example where the graph has certain properties: for example, if formula_24 counts graphs without cycles, then formula_22 counts trees (connected graphs without cycles).
* If formula_24 counts directed graphs whose (rather than vertices) are a given formula_12 point set, then formula_22 counts connected directed graphs with this edge set.
*In quantum field theory and statistical mechanics, the partition functions formula_48, or more generally correlation functions, are given by a formal sum over Feynman diagrams. The exponential formula shows that formula_49 can be written as a sum over connected Feynman diagrams, in terms of connected correlation functions.

