where formula_5 is the out-of-plane electric field, formula_6 is the characteristic inflow velocity, and formula_7 is the characteristic upstream magnetic field strength. By neglecting displacement current, the low-frequency Ampere&#x27;s law, formula_8, gives the relation
formula_9

where formula_10 is the current sheet half-thickness. This relation uses that the magnetic field reverses over a distance of formula_11. By matching the ideal electric field outside of the layer with the resistive electric field formula_12 inside the layer (using Ohm&#x27;s law), we find that
formula_13

where formula_14 is the magnetic diffusivity. When the inflow density is comparable to the outflow density, conservation of mass yields the relationship
formula_15

where formula_16 is the half-length of the current sheet and formula_17 is the outflow velocity. The left and right hand sides of the above relation represent the mass flux into the layer and out of the layer, respectively. Equating the upstream magnetic pressure with the downstream dynamic pressure gives
formula_18

where formula_19 is the mass density of the plasma. Solving for the outflow velocity then gives
